792. ⁴ If any antiquity can ever gain belief for so great a deed.’ Mere antiquity from a poet's point of view is one of the strongest grounds for believing in ancient legends. So Ovid, speaking of the stones thrown by Deucalion and Pyrrha being changed into human beings, says (M. i. 400) quis hoc credat, nisi sic pro teste vetustas?

800. dum abiret] ‘until he should retire': dum, ‘untiL’ regularly takes subj. when it refers not to time merely, but to time as purposed in the mind of somebody. Here it is their purpose to cover his retreat : R. 692. Cp. inf. 809. Note the change of sequence in abiret after secuntur: the past tense is used because the poet throws himself back into the past, to the time of the event.
